Hawaii

🦁🏋️‍♀️🎊 Day 2️⃣5️⃣ of #CoreUproar with @cyogalife ➡️ Reclined #Splits or #SuptaTrivikramasana 🎊🏋️‍♀️🦁
What is today’s pose doing here, you might ask? Giving us a break, that is, phew! It’s also an appropriate stretch for the upcoming last 3 days. I like to practice this Splits variant because it’s tougher (also safer for the hamstrings), to open the legs completely. On the regular version, gravity and the floor are strong assistants so, if you’ve had a small injury for instance, or you’ve overstretched the hamstrings and they’re extra sensitive, chances are the usual version might be too strong. The reclined one lets you decide how much you want to pull in, and it’s overall a more active lengthening. Warm up legs beforehand, then lie down and start to bring one in, keep chest/hips facing up (it’s tempting to open slightly and ‘follow’ what the leg is doing, don’t!), imagine a straight line, from the heel of the leg you’re pulling, to the toes of the other. As leg gets closer to the face, move it slightly towards the ear, still maintaining that straight line, head to toe. Use upper body to pull in but let the hamstrings and flexors lengthen gradually as you hold longer & breathe fuller. One way to deepen it (and make it less work for the arms) is to put a couple of ankle weights/sandbags on each leg. Lengthen torso, reach through crown of the head, pull navel in and notice where you feel limited or stuck. If you can stay for 1-2 minutes, do so and see if there’s any changes. Adapt it to your needs, be smart about it and, for those of you who don’t need the break, revisit the asanas done in the past few days to get ready for tomorrow...😎
For alternatives, check out @yogawithaislinn and @katydoesyoga
